article.description: Adrain Williams had 12 points and 10 rebounds as the Phoenix Mercury snapped a six-game losing streak and held the Lynx to their lowest point total in franchise history in a 57-45 triumph.
article.headline: Mercury find some success at home
article.linkText: Mercury snap six-game losing streak with win over Lynx
article.story:
PHOENIX -- Adrain Williams had 12 points and 10 rebounds as
the Phoenix Mercury snapped a six-game losing streak by beating the
Minnesota Lynx 57-45 Monday night.

      Jaynetta Saunders scored a career-high 12 points, and Jennifer
Gillom had 10 for the Mercury (9-16), who have lost a WNBA-record
18 straight road games but improved to 9-4 at home.

      Minnesota (7-18) has lost 11 straight road games, one short of
Phoenix's 0-12 record this season.

      Svetlana Abrosimova had 13 points, and Michele Van Gorp added 10
points and eight rebounds for the Lynx. But Katie Smith, who set
seven WNBA season scoring records last year and had 19 points in a
loss at Sacramento the previous night, made only one of 15 field
goals and tied her career-low with two points in 35 minutes.

      "It's great to get a home win and see the team play with such
passion," Mercury coach Linda Sharp said. "I thought we played
really hard tonight. We set some records, we held Minnesota to
their season-low, and Katie Smith, one of the best shooters in the
league, didn't get a basket until close to the end."

      Saunders and Lisa Harrison took turns guarding Smith, who was
scoreless until she made a layup with 1:41 to play, cutting
Minnesota's deficit to 53-43.

      "I got some good looks," Smith said. "I just didn't knock
them down. They didn't do anything different to me. This has just
been a different year."

      The Lynx hit season lows for points and field goal percentage
(.320) and had a season-high 25 turnovers, with Harrison and
Williams getting three steals apiece.

      "Our main key tonight was defense," Saunders said. "I think
we did a pretty good job. I was so anxious to come out there and
help the team a little bit."

      The Lynx made an all-out effort to snap their skid in the first
half, jumping ahead 16-2 on a turnaround by Van Gorp 5:01 in.

      But the Mercury battled back and took a 26-25 lead on a layup by
Adriana Moises with 40.7 to play in the first half. Williams made
it 28-25 at halftime on a buzzer-beating layup after a pass from
Moises.

      The Mercury went on a 9-1 run in the first 3:09 of the second
half, taking a 37-26 lead.

      "We were on a good roll, weren't we?" Lynx coach Heidi
VanDerveer said. "I wish it had stayed. We got the same shots most
of the half. We got some easy shots in transition early, got them
spread out a bit. Then some of the shots we got in the last 30
minutes we just didn't make."
